Prolog
"I beg you!" Queen Eirwen pleaded, "don't send her away! She's still a child!" The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought of it, his expression darkened.
The girl resembled her mother very much. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue streaks. A girl meant weakness in the eyes of the Ice King. After all, up to that point, he had only fathered sons.
"You have two choices: Either you kill the child or you send it into the wilderness. That is his punishment for your failure, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poisonous. He always did.
Frostfell had not always been a single kingdom. Previously, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. In the North lay the non-magical kingdom, while the South was a kingdom full of fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed, and an endless war broke out between the two kingdoms, until finally the South offered a ceasefire.
The despair in the South was so great that the royal family was willing to do anything to end the bloodshed. They offered to send their only princess as queen to the North, where she was to give birth to a son, the future king. In this case, the North would unite with the South to form a single kingdom. The North accepted the proposal, and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
"I beg you, my king, do with me whatever you wish—imprison me, banish me, or kill me, but spare my child," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down on his queen in full contempt. Perhaps, but only perhaps, he would have mercy on her. The woman with whom he had been married for 22 years, who had stood by him in his worst times and had given him his sons.
"Alright. The child may remain in the palace," he said, which the queen acknowledged with a sigh. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked at each other in horror. Slowly, she lowered her gaze to the floor. "Yes, my king." She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter into one of Eirwen's empty rooms. Afterwards, he commanded the guards to take Eirwen to the execution square, where all the citizens of the city could watch.
As the guards escorted her to the execution site, a loud uproar broke out among the citizens when they realized that their beloved queen was about to be executed. Some people wept, others screamed and attacked the guards. Still others wondered why this was happening, but all were in agreement.
"Let them go!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The Pyre Judge. The woman who had just been queen was to be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the worst thing that could be done to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech how the queen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the king and would not accept his words. Then the executioner set the wooden stake alight, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Don't give up, Kari." This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Dead silence in the palace.
Only a knock could be heard from the room located all the way to the left in the southern wing of the eternally cold palace. The servants who passed by always wondered what was in that room. They were afraid of it. Rumors spread among the maids in the palace. Allegedly, the deceased wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in that room, waiting to be let out.
Her suspicion couldn't have been more wrong, thought Ivory, as she headed toward the south wing, while the servants walked about and whispered among themselves. They had no idea what lay behind the door.
Of course, the rumors also concerned Ivory, since Ivory was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. "Lady Kari, are you in there?" whispered Ivory in front of the beautifully decorated door adorned with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered whether, unlike the last time, they would actually be allowed in. I still have bruises from the last time," Ivory giggled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book at Ivory's shoulder but immediately apologized when she realized whom she had hit.
A single knock could be heard from inside, probably to indicate that she was there. Where else could she be?
"May I come in?" asked Ivory. Earlier, Ivory had walked in without asking.
From inside, Ivory heard a knock. That probably meant a "Yes." The cold and the sound made Ivory shiver. It felt strange to hear a sound coming from a room supposedly empty, even though Ivory had been going in there for several years already.
"I'm coming in," said Ivory, and slowly opened the door. The sight that greeted Ivory in the room was unusual for normal people, but not unexpected for Ivory. Paper was everywhere. Books were scattered around, the desk was broken, and several ice sculptures lay about. There were no windows and little to no light. Moreover, it was colder than the rest of the palace (which said a lot). The room looked as if a snowstorm had swept through it.
The girl lay curled up in her bed, wrapped in her blanket, and was reading from one of her notebooks. A small lamp lit up the room.
"What notebook is that?" Ivory asked and sat down next to Kari on the bed.
